spanGrp.span: ‘Here our clan kills the chiken from the backyard.
Jiska sa ditseiwa të óshkoro te-gẽ rö óshkoro tsõ jũ í töinga
They take care of them with fruits and things;
Óshkoro tsõ kunãnẽ-gẽ í wakwa të kalwö wa jiro wa
and raise many of them, roosters and hens.
óshkoro kebiwẽ-gẽ-ite tã'ĩ je yerriwa óshkoro mĩnã wa
They kill chickens that do not lay eggs
óshoro/ mẽnẽũ óshkoro-wa ka sĩã' tsõ je-wa je-wa te-ke-gẽ-wã
by hanging them from a rope.
jie-wa të í mwẽ-gẽ-wã í kuli ska ksa wa
When they run out of air [oxigen], they die.
Je wa jie-wa kichkemẽ-gẽ-ga ska í siwã' mĩ-gẽũ-ra óshkoro döá-wã
And there they cook the chicken in a pot
Jeska ra jie-wa të óshkoro eliwẽ-gẽ-nẽ olla jãrga jirö nã
and search for fruits, like plantains, pumpkins and mirlitons
Jie-wa mĩ-gẽ-nẽ kalwö yulö chomõwö jarwö piswö
and cook a lot of food. They cook it well.
je wa jie-wa të í eliwẽ-gẽ tã'ĩ (hm) elir-wã köũ báwã ska
Then they serve it to these who are going to eat.
Jeska nẽ jie-wa të í blatie-gẽ-nẽ (_) mẽnẽwã tsõ yögö-gẽ-wã ĩã
That’s how we kill the chicken.’
Jebi jie-wa të óshkoro te-gẽ rö
